'''Cannabis in [[Bhutan]]''' is illegal, but grows prolifically in the country and has multiple traditional uses, such as feeding pigs and producing textiles.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Bhutan|journal=UNODC: South Asia Regional Profile|date=September 2005|url=https://www.unodc.org/pdf/india/publications/south_Asia_Regional_Profile_Sept_2005/09_bhutan.pdf}}</ref>

==Popularization==
Awareness of cannabis as a drug seems limited in Bhutan, with some authorities tracing its arrival to the legalization of television in 1999; prior to that point, cannabis was mostly thought of as a fodder to fatten pigs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2003/jun/14/weekend7.weekend2 |title=Fast forward into trouble |publisher=The Guardian |date=2003-06-13 |accessdate=2016-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2016895.stm |title=Bhutan's growing cannabis problem |publisher=BBC News |date=2002-05-30 |accessdate=2016-11-30}}</ref> The [[International Narcotics Control Board]] noted in 2002 that Bhutan had no history of cannabis abuse, but the government had recently raised concerns about drug abuse, particularly by the young, and taken an interest in eradicating wild cannabis and counseling drug users.<ref>{{cite book|title=Report of the International Narcotics Control Board for 2002|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k7IfxQ5mnEMC&pg=PA57|year=2003|publisher=United Nations Publications|isbn=978-92-1-148154-9|pages=57–}}</ref>

==Enforcement==
Bhutan's first arrest for drug abuse occurred in 1989 in [[Gelephu]], where a man was arrested for abusing cannabis.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://thebhutanese.bt/41-dead-and-counting-bhutans-growing-drug-problem/ |title=41 dead and counting: Bhutan’s growing Drug problem – The Bhutanese |publisher=Thebhutanese.bt |date= |accessdate=2016-11-30}}</ref>

In 2010 the Bhutanese government seized 4kg of cannabis; in 2011 this increased to 75kg.<ref>https://www.incb.org/documents/Publications/AnnualReports/AR2012/AR_2012_E_Chapter_III_Asia.pdf</ref>

==Textiles==
Though the wild nettle is the more common source of traditional textiles, cannabis has also been used for its fibre, and is called ''kenam'' in the [[Dzongkha language]].<ref name="Altmann2016">{{cite book|author=Karin Altmann|title=Fabric of Life - Textile Arts in Bhutan: Culture, Tradition and Transformation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ZNlCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA235|date=1 January 2016|publisher=De Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-042861-2|pages=235–}}</ref>

