'''Lake Karapiro''' is an artificial [[reservoir]] lake on the [[Waikato River]], {{convert|30|km}} south-east of the city of [[Hamilton, New Zealand|Hamilton]] in New Zealand's [[North Island]]. The lake was formed in 1947 by damming the Waikato River to store water for the 96-megawatt [[Karapiro Power Station|Karapiro hydroelectric power station]].<ref name="lowe">{{cite book| editor = Viner, A.B.| author=Lowe, D.J., Green, J.D.| title=Inland waters of New Zealand| pages=471–474| publisher=DSIR Science Information Publishing Centre| location=Wellington| year=1987| isbn=0-477-06799-9}}</ref>

== Etymology ==
'Kara' means stone (dark basalt), 'piro' means evil-smelling. According to legend, Karapiro was the stronghold of the chief O-Te-Ihingarangi, and was where the Ngati Haua and their [[Tauranga]] allies made a defensive pact during the [[New Zealand land wars|land wars]] of 1864.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.mightyriverpower.co.nz/Generation/AboutUs/HydroStations/Karapiro/Default.aspx| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610051858/http://www.mightyriverpower.co.nz/Generation/PowerStations/HydroStations/Karapiro/Default.aspx?id=1425| title=Karapiro - History| deadurl=yes| archivedate=10 June 2011| publisher=Mighty River Power}}</ref>

== Rowing venue ==
The lake, regarded as one of New Zealand's best [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]] venues, hosted the [[World Rowing Championships]] in [[1978 World Rowing Championships|1978]] and [[2010 World Rowing Championships|2010]], as well as the rowing events for the [[1950 British Empire Games]]. Lake Karapiro alternates with the South Island's [[Lake Ruataniwha]] in hosting the New Zealand national rowing championships and the New Zealand secondary school rowing championships ([[Maadi Cup]]). Rowers who train on the lake mostly live in nearby [[Cambridge, New Zealand|Cambridge]].

An [[International Rowing Federation]] inspection panel visited Lake Karapiro in March 2006 and said in its report that it was one of the fairest courses in the world they had seen and that the lake was one of the most picturesque in the world.<ref name="NZ_Herald_10385584">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/story.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10385584 |title=NZ to host 2010 world rowing champs |date=8 June 2006 |agency=[[NZPA]] |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=13 October 2011}}</ref>

==Hydroelectric power==
The 96-megawatt [[Karapiro Power Station]] is located adjacent to the dam at the head of the lake, and is the eighth and last hydroelectric power station located on the Waikato River. Water for the power station up to {{convert|362|m3/s}} at full power, is taken from the lake and passed through three Kaplan turbines in the powerhouse, before being deposited into the lower Waikato River. Each turbine turns a 32&nbsp;MW generator, and the electricity from the generators is fed into [[Transpower New Zealand Limited|Transpower]]'s [[National Grid (New Zealand)|national transmission grid]]. The station is a [[base load power plant|base load generator]] due to its need to maintain water flows into the Waikato River system beyond the lake.

The ten-megawatt [[Horahora Power Station]] at Horahora, 13&nbsp;km upstream of Karapiro Dam, part of an earlier hydroelectric power scheme, was flooded with the formation of Lake Karapiro.<ref>{{cite book|last=Martin|first=John E. |title= People, politics and power stations : electric power generation in New Zealand, 1880–1990|year=1991|isbn=0-908912-16-1}}</ref>

